<subSubSection id="C33659F6FFDB9F31FF45FA02FC91AE3F" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B930A7DFFDB9F31FF45FA02FC92A84C" blockId="8.[189,1399,839,975]" box="[189,863,839,865]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Hardwicke’s descriptive statement for this name is slight:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B930A7DFFDB9F31FF45FA2EFC42A8E2" blockId="8.[189,1399,839,975]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
“ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C71FEFFDB9F31FF32FA29FDBAA8A8" authority="Montana, Roxburgh." authorityName="Montana, Roxburgh." box="[202,631,875,902]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lythraceae" genus="Lagerstroemia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958D66FFFDB9F31FF32FA29FE24A8A8" box="[202,489,876,901]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Lagerstroemia Montana</emphasis>
, Roxburgh.
</taxonomicName>
— This tree grows to sixty or seventy feet high. Stem straight, thick, and clear of branches to a great height (forty feet). Flowers with much beauty in the month of May. Grows both above and below the ghats. Trees not numerous.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B930A7DFFDB9F31FF45FAB2FC91AE3F" blockId="8.[189,1399,1015,1298]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The name appears never to have been taken up elsewhere. There are three similar drawings in the British Library collection (Vol. X nos. 30–32) that represent this species. The first is annotated ‘Coadwara 
<date id="FF922CBDFFDB9F31FF45FD05FE9BAF77" box="[189,342,1088,1115]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1796-05-06">6 May 1796</date>
’; the second has a note saying ‘No. 66 Cor Pl. vol 1’. This citation of Roxburgh’s 
<emphasis id="B958D66FFFDB9F31FAD3FD04FDDAAF52" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Plants of the Coast of Coromandel</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFBD778CFFDB9F31FDD3FD20FD24AFAD" author="Roxburgh W." box="[555,745,1125,1152]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref10132" refString="Roxburgh W. 1795 - 1820. Plants of the Coast of Coromandel. W. Bulmer &amp; Co., London. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 467" type="book" year="1795">
Roxburgh 
<date id="FF922CBDFFDB9F31FD57FD20FD24AFAD" box="[687,745,1125,1152]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1795" valueMax="1820">1795</date>
</bibRefCitation>
– 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBD778CFFDB9F31FD01FD20FCF9AFAD" author="Roxburgh W." box="[761,820,1125,1152]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref10171" refString="Roxburgh W. 1820. Flora Indica. First edition. Volume 1. Mission Press, Serampore." type="book" year="1820">1820</bibRefCitation>
) refers to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C71FEFFDB9F31FC44FD23FABAAF52" authority="Roxb. The" authorityName="Roxb. The" authorityYear="1795" box="[956,1399,1125,1151]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lythraceae" genus="Lagerstroemia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parviflora">
<emphasis id="B958D66FFFDB9F31FC44FD23FB24AF52" box="[956,1257,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Lagerstroemia parviflora</emphasis>
Roxb. The
</taxonomicName>
drawings match 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C71FEFFDB9F31FE7FFDCEFDD2AF89" authorityName="Roxb. The" authorityYear="1795" box="[391,543,1162,1188]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lythraceae" genus="Lagerstroemia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parviflora">
<emphasis id="B958D66FFFDB9F31FE7FFDCEFDD2AF89" box="[391,543,1162,1188]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. parviflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was published before 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C71FEFFDB9F31FC6BFDCEFBD0AF89" box="[915,1053,1163,1188]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lythraceae" genus="Lagerstroemia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="B958D66FFFDB9F31FC6BFDCEFBD0AF89" box="[915,1053,1163,1188]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, it seems best to consider 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C71FEFFDB9F31FED6FDEAFD82AFE5" box="[302,591,1199,1224]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lythraceae" genus="Lagerstroemia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="B958D66FFFDB9F31FED6FDEAFD82AFE5" box="[302,591,1199,1224]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Lagerstroemia montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as an invalidly published name. Surprisingly, Roxburgh did not originally recognise his own species, writing in 
<date id="FF922CBDFFDB9F31FD00FD96FC5DAFC0" box="[760,912,1235,1261]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1797-08">August 1797</date>
that Hardwicke’s plant was “a charming new 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C71FEFFDB9F31FF0DFDBDFE6CAE3C" box="[245,417,1272,1297]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lythraceae" genus="Lagerstroemia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958D66FFFDB9F31FF0DFDBDFE6CAE3C" box="[245,417,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Lagerstroemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.... you must give it a specific name”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
